 <fr:p>We will argue from a combinatoric perspective.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>An <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injection</fr:link> <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> from <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> associates no more than one <fr:tex>a \in  A</fr:tex> to the same <fr:tex>b \in  B</fr:tex>. Thus if we consider the subset <fr:tex>U \subseteq  B</fr:tex> spanned by elements of the form <fr:tex>f { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>, we should then get a <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>U</fr:tex>as each <fr:tex>b \in  U</fr:tex> comes from a <fr:em>unique</fr:em> <fr:tex>a \in  A</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Therefore, choosing an <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injection</fr:link> amounts to making <fr:em>two</fr:em> independent choices: first we choose a subset of <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> that is in <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link> with <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>, and then we choose a <fr:em>specific</fr:em> <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to that subset. The number of such subsets is precisely <fr:tex>\mathord { \# } {B} \choose   \mathord { \# } {A}</fr:tex>, and we have already seen in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00KT"
href="jms-00KT.xml"
taxon="Proposition"></fr:ref> that the number of such bijections is the factorial <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( \mathord { \# } {A}! \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Of course, if there is no subset of <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> equinumerous with <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>, then there can be no <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injection</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:contributions></fr:contributions><fr:context><fr:tree
